data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assert methods. Your current code works but gives poor failure messages. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | You already know the exact count; assert it directly for a clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | `Assert.IsTrue(cond, "msg")` | Add a message — bare `IsTrue` just says "expected true, got false" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Semantic clarity + better failure output |
| `users.Single()` (throws) | `users.SingleOrDefault()` + `Assert.IsNotNull` | Keeps the test failure in the assert, not an unhandled exception |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify exact contents (order-insensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Verify exact contents + order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Membership checks
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, specificUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);
```

Use `Assert.AreEqual` / `Assert.IsNotNull` for scalar checks, and `CollectionAssert` when comparing or validating entire collections.
